            <div class="carousel-item">
              <%= image_tag "126-choice.png", class: "d-block w-100" %>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a class="carousel-control-prev" href="#carouselExampleControls" role="button" data-slide="prev">
            <span class="carousel-control-prev-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
            <span class="sr-only">Previous</span>
          </a>
          <a class="carousel-control-next" href="#carouselExampleControls" role="button" data-slide="next">
            <span class="carousel-control-next-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
            <span class="sr-only">Next</span>
          </a>
        </div>
        <div class="description">
          <p>Apparently, people spend 18 minutes a day scrolling Netflix in search of something to watch. This, combined with the tension of cooking, can be pretty annoying on a Friday night. Enter <%= link_to "126", "http://www.onetwosix.co.uk/", class: "project-link" %>. This MVC app will suggest film and food combos based on a movie genre and cuisine chosen by the user, and once a combo is chosen it will take the user to the movie on Netflix and to the restaurant on Deliveroo.</p>
          <p>The user simply has to add their postcode, combine a movie genre and food type and can then browse through the options provided by the app. The options are limited only by the number of restaurants signed up with Deliveroo in the area. We achieved this by scraping the Deliveroo platform for open restaurants within the postcode entered corresponding with the chosen cuisine, and by parsing Netflix movie titles using an API. We also included an automated Youtube search for movie trailers, and the option for restaurant owners on Deliveroo to join the platform and sponsor a combo to give their restaurant a boost. The app is hosted by Heroku.</p>
          <p>My team at Le Wagon and I built this app in less than 10 days, during the last two weeks of the bootcamp. We had already decided on the flow and on the overall user journey previously, using Figma and Whimsical, but during production I styled the site, made it responsive on all devices and integrated the carousel using JavaScript. On demo night my team and I presented the app in front of an audience at the Google Start-up Campus in London.</p>
        </div>
